ID:625_157052614454466
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:One last message from me.  Looking forward, we are preparing for the June/July 2013 Winter Program!  Today, Todd and Tara Humphreys, Mike and Liza Silvestri, Richard Kelley, and I met to plan for next program and beyond.

Most of us in this group have had valuable first hand experience in Mamelodi, and some of us even grew up in Mamelodi.  So we would LOVE assistance with any of the following.

0. Pray for Mamelodi and the South African and US volunteers.
1. Prepare maths and English lesson plans for this June.
2. Partnership development.  This is an exciting area: thanks, Cynthia Ayeza for developing the partnership with the Nelson Mandela Rhodes Scholars program!
3. Recruiting.  We have room to recruit many more US volunteers, especially men, but there is definitely room for both.  And way to go on South African recruiting; today I heard something incredible like ~80 potential volunteers.
4. Last year we had to turn many kids away from the Winter program.  So pray for wisdom as we decide how to expand to the surrounding area and beyond.  Ideas/suggestions are welcome.
5. The Mamelodi Initiative is officially a US 501c3 non-profit organization.  This is just awesome, that is all.  Thanks, God :-)

In case you're wondering, computer nerds count from 0.  But anyway, I'll be helping coordinate the 2013 Winter Program preparation team.  Send me a message if you want to be a part of it!

Message:Do you have a passion for math or science and love working with kids? If so, join Inspire! Inspire is a volunteer placement organization that helps UNC students get involved in science and math classrooms in local Chapel Hill and Carrboro public schools. We place UNC students with teachers in CHCCS to help students get the help they need to succeed in science or math courses, from elementary to high school. We will work with your schedule and interests to find the placement that is right for you! Message:Hey UNC friends! Sign up to be an International Orientation Counselor for Fall 2014!

Upon my return to the beautiful land of America in the fall I will be working with UNC International Office of Student and Scholar Services at the FedEx Global Center as an Orientation Counselor, and I hope you can join me! Some of you have volunteered before and know it's loads of fun! You will help with the check in process, make copies, answer basic questions, welcome international students to UNC, and make new friends (I heard that there are a lot of attractive Danes and Hong Kongers coming, so this is your chance).

Message:So the annual spring jazz events are coming up this weekend and who doesn't like a little Basie in the springtime? The UNC Jazz Band will be playing some classic tunes from The Atomic Basie record, along with a couple student arrangements by Brian Bray and Nathan Huvard. Name:How Wall Street recruits so many insecure Ivy League grads
Story:N/A
Message:Insightful article on how Wall Street got the talents, and why the magic starts to fail.

The interesting thing is how Teach For America smartly copies the model for a non-profit. Can we copy that to HK for the non-profits too? It sounds a bit difficult due to the lack of top liberal arts colleges, lack of industrial diversity and immature environment for post graduate occupational education like MBA and JD. The third one is improving but no sign for the first and second...However, the psychology of students is similar in HK and US after all,which means it should be able to draw some great talents, if not as successful as Teach For America in the States. Right?

Arnold Chan Elaine Cheng Geoffrey Cheuk Keith Poon Venus Leung Wendy Leung Tingie Charmaine Chan

ID:708705302_10152032127220303
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

Message:I had a great Sunday at Christ the King Moravian Church with some of our Moravian students from UNC-Chapel Hill, NC State, Elon, and Central Carolina Community College!  Besides enjoying the worship service, we had a nice luncheon filled with pizza, sharing, singing, and a game of trivia.  Thanks Alex (UNC and Kernersville), Caitlin (NCSU and Olivet), Daniel (NCSU and Olivet), Doug (CCCC and Christ the King), Isaac (UNC and Olivet), Kelly (Elon and Olivet), Meghan (UNC and Calvary), Jason (soon to be Vanderbilt Grad School and Olivet), Julie (UNC and Olivet), Tessa (soon to be UNC Dental School and Christ the King), and Zach (NCSU and King) for being there!  It was great having two of Christ the King's high school seniors, Allen and Rachel, with us, and they will be at Carolina this fall.  It was also great being with Stephanie (Duke Divinity School) and her husband, David, and plans are for Stephanie to be the College and Young Adult intern for Christ the King this fall.  Special thanks to the Rev. Frank Venable, pastor at Christ the King, and Corey Whittaker, Youth Director at Christ the King, for their great hospitality!

ID:1314908097_10204224782802486
Name:Why Vincent Chin Matters
Story:N/A
Message:I want to take this time to remember Vincent Chin, Asian American who was an unfortunate victim of racism and discrimination against Asian Americans in the U.S. Though his death was a tragedy and affected many, his legacy sparked the modern Asian American civil movement, and the echoes of his impact still can be heard today. Let us all take this time to remember his death, and most importantly, let us all take this time to reflect on the discrimination against Asian Americans that still exists today. If you think this issue is far from you, then you aren't looking close enough.

ID:1314908097_10204149420478475
Name:CET Janterm/Spring 2014
Story:N/A
Message:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rb5BSCPli6k

After about a month living in China, I realized that my camera had this really cool feature on it that was able to take photos and videos SIMULTANEOUSLY. Thus, during my travels, explorations, and adventures, I was able to capture a lot of precious memories.

Sometimes, photos can't always tell the full story. Granted, nothing can really take the place of the actual experience. However, with these little snapshots, I was able to capture the little moments right before the click of the shutter - sometimes I got a video of somebody dancing, or a face popping in and disappearing right before a click, or a switch of a facial expression. So, here's my video of all these little clips and other recordings that i've collected, and I hope that everyone can get a real taste of my semester abroad!

To my CET family: look out for yourself in the video! :)
Also --view in full screen!
ID:1314908097_10204148059564453
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:And with that, my time in Beijing comes to an end. I can't begin to thank the people that have been in my life for the past few months, the people who have become my family here. There's no way to stay in the moments past, but by pressing forward we carry those memories with us into the future. I will most definitely miss you guys, but this won't be our last meeting by any means, for as long as the soil beneath our feet is solid, the path we take will lead us back to one another again. For now though, I bid farewell to the city of Beijing. Shanghai, I don't think you're ready for what's about to come.

Story:N/A
Message:O Captain! My Captain! our fearful trip is done;
The ship has weather'd every rack, the prize we sought is won;
The port is near, the bells I hear, the people all exulting,
While follow eyes the steady keel, the vessel grim and daring:

But O heart! heart! heart!
O the bleeding drops of red,
Where on the deck my Captain lies,
Fallen cold and dead.
O Captain! My Captain! rise up and hear the bells;
Rise up?for you the flag is flung?for you the bugle trills;
For you bouquets and ribbon'd wreaths?for you the shores a-crowding;
For you they call, the swaying mass, their eager faces turning;

Here captain! dear father!
This arm beneath your head;
It is some dream that on the deck,
You've fallen cold and dead.
My Captain does not answer, his lips are pale and still;
My father does not feel my arm, he has no pulse nor will;
The ship is anchor'd safe and sound, its voyage closed and done;
From fearful trip, the victor ship, comes in with object won;

Exult, O shores, and ring, O bells!
But I, with mournful tread,
Walk the deck my captain lies,
Fallen cold and dead.

How I wish you can come back to me, o captain, my captain.

ID:1531609000_10201669923259817
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

Message:And now... As most of you can guess.. My journey has come to an end! After 2 continents, 11 countries, and 2 1/2 months of so many different cities I can officially say Europe was an incredible experience! I want to thank the friends I traveled with Brett Wedel and Kyle Wayne Kroeker  for making every part of this trip unforgettable! Message:I was suggested to read a book "Confessions of a Medical Heretic" by M.D. Robert S. Mendelsohn. Here's a part of Stephen Pletko's comment on Amazon: 

Each chapter (there are nine) of this book has many truths. These truths are not out-of-date and will probably remain relevant into the far future. Here are just three examples:

1) "Every drug stresses and hurts your body in some way."
2) "A healthy society is characterized by strong, positive family relationships and subsequent minimal need of doctors."
3) "Doctors are not trained to attack the core of any problem, merely to suppress symptoms."

I am so glad to see that UNC has this book in its library.

ID:100000291936863_784277821591942
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

Message:So basically Idina Menzel is really good at being Elsa because "Frozen"="Wicked". Hear me out:
-Recasting a witch from a well-known tale into a sympathetic, misunderstood young woman who is learning to control her powers that she's had since birth
-The main character's father tells her to hide her power
-The main character is trying to watch out for her younger sister to the best of her abilities
-Little sister falls for a man who couldn't give a crap about her
-Main character is ostracized and exiled by the frightened mob who are led to believe that she is a monster
-Both main characters sing an iconic, sassy song that expresses their new found freedom and decision not to play by society's rules anymore ("Let It Go"="Defying Gravity")
-Both main characters retreat to a hideaway and have scary minions to keep people out (flying monkeys/guards= giant snowman)
-Both main characters realize that despite her best intentions, she's still placed people in harm's way (Fiyero being captured, Arendelle being thrown into winter)
-A villain realizes that the best way to emotionally affect the witch is through her sister
-A character unintentionally plays the sister into the villain's plans (Kristoff, Glinda: who are both blondes, btw)
-Both characters wear a piece of clothing that is iconic to her style (witch's hat, gloves, cape)
The only differences are the personalities of the younger sisters (Anna and Nessarose) and the endings. Oh, what's that? I've blown your mind? Understandable.

ID:100000747192568_377574025657986
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Hey, Sustainability. As I said, Brett and I are putting together a Relay for Life team. It should be a lot of fun. It is not an actual race, but there are a number of events for fundraising and such culminating in the night in April when we all camp out on Fetzer Field. We can put together fundraising events that count towards social and/or external engagement hours! We'll talk about those later. To sign up, 

1. Go to uncrelay.org 
2. click on the orange "Sign Up" button
3. Click on the orange "Join an existing team button"
4. Type "Relaying Rams" in the text box and click "Next"
5. Fill out the rest of the stuff. A minimum $10 donation is required to participate. It goes to a good cause, the American Cancer Society!

"Relaying Rams" was not my idea. I'm looking to change the name to a catchy acronym like IMHOCIKOB (In My Humble Opinion Cancer Is Kind Of Bad) or THIC (Tree Huggers Intimidating Cancer). Let's do it.

ID:100001043113693_771080102936753
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

Story:Zinnia Kong shared an event.
Message:Hi everyone!
My name is Ziyin (Zinnia) Kong and I am a sophomore who just started to live off-campus this semester. I am currently a member of two university committees: public safety and disability committee. 
Living off-campus makes our time schedule more flexible and gives us more individual spaces, while it can also raise our concern about off-campus safety and transportation problem. The lightening system on South Street may make you feel unsafe when walking alone during the midnight. Moreover, the Waltham shuttle which runs each thirty minutes is always full and you don?t actually know when to call in or when will you get picked up. You may also get frustrated when you miss school activities simply because you are living off-campus, where nobody put posters on your front doors. What?s more, you could be so angry and upset when you drive your car to the school and find all spots have already full.
As one of the students live off-campus who is willing to stand out for everyone who lives off-campus, I would specify put my effort on improving the public transfer system and the safety around the school area, and solving the problem for parking spots. I would also cope with other members in the student union to spread news and announcement and make sure off-campus students receive it. 
If you need help or have concerns about living off-campus, I would also be here to listen and help! Vote for me and I would show you my passion!

Message:Sales & Marketing High School Representatives (Now Accepting Applications!)

To those who are now studying at U.S. high schools:
Are you interested in real-world business? Do you want to show your leadership skills through meaningful extracurricular experiences? Are you seeking ways to make a real impact on your community? Do you want to join a company run by top U.S. college students and earn management positions in your college years?

Then join us! We partner with Findingschool.net and have established the ?Finding Your Leaper Program?. As a Sales & Marketing Representative at the U.S. high schools, you would collaborate with top U.S. college students to carry out marketing plans, improve our services and gain first-hand exposure to the business world. 

Benefits:
1. Great resume boost for college application
2. Networking opportunities with college students from Harvard, Princeton, UPenn, Duke and many more!
3. Opportunities to show your leadership, marketing and business skills
4. A possibility to take management-level positions in college years
5. Rewards available from sales

Requirements:
1. A junior or senior in a U.S. high school
2. Outstanding performance in academic and extracurricular activities
3. Great communication skills
4. Responsible and able to meet time commitment (1-3 hours/week)
5. Ability to effectively reach out to targeted student populations

Responsibilities:
1. Design and execute a local marketing strategy with the goal of growing awareness and participation in Leap
2. Develop original content, including videos, stories, posters, and other multimedia assets to promote Leap
3. Other job duties as assigned

Deadline?January 25th?2013

How to apply?
Please write a short essay (less than 250 words) about why you want to join Leap and how you would contribute to our program. Please email your essay and your most recent academic transcript to leap.program.usa@gmail.com

After receiving your application, we will conduct phone interviews to qualified candidates. We would accept candidates on a rolling basis. Since the spots fill up quickly, please apply as soon as possible. The last day to apply is January 25th, 2013, but we are very likely to close our admission before then.

Please check more relevant information at: www.leap-usa.com
We are looking forward to speaking with you about your interests!



Leap Consulting Co.Ltd.
A Peer Mentor Program for International Students at U.S. High Schools
www.leap-usa.com
leap.program.usa@gmail.com

ID:100002739888196_477597969008195
Name:null
Story:Crystalcrazy Zheng was tagged in Chenming Richard Mo's photo.
Message:N/A
ID:100002739888196_476660382435287
Name:null
Story:Crystalcrazy Zheng added 9 photos.
Message:I was asked before those 24 hours whether dancers should be there all the 24 hours. ?They should be there the whole time?? ?No one would know if they leave right?? To be honest, I had the same question back then as well. I even thought that ?stand? meant just staying there rather than literally standing. If you were tired, you could sit; if you were sleepy, you could simply sleep on the ground. 

I was asked before those 24 hours whether dancers kept dancing the whole time. ?What is the point of standing for 24 hours? I understand why dancers need to raise at least 150 dollars but I can?t figure out why they should be standing for that long? I felt the same way and had no idea how to response. 

I was asked before those 24 hours about why I was in the committee of DM. ?What can you gain out of this organization?? I was kind of tongue-tied at that moment and did not really know the answer myself.

It was finally Friday night, the night of the 16th annual DM. 

In the first six or seven hours, everyone was in high spirits and was full of energy; the place was like a giant dancing floor of a bar that could hold and was holding thousands of people. Different from a bar, people inside were not excited and elated by alcohol; rather, with a sober mind and for a pure and wonderful dream, they gathered together in the same place and danced better than any dancers in any single bar. 

When it was 3ish am, I wondered why there were much fewer people in the gym, only to find that a lot of them went to the study room to lean on the table, or stood on their heads on the wall, or put their feet on the handrails of the stairs, or helped others to lift up their legs. Anyway there were all sorts of funny and cute poses that could help ease the pain. Yet no matter how exhausted and painful, there was not even a single person on the spot breaking the promise made before; there was not even a single person trying to sit down for just a little while. I heard people say something like ?I want my bed?, ?I?ve never wanted to sit on the ground so bad?, ?I can?t feel my feet? and ?We got this we can do it? but I didn?t hear anything like ?Let?s just sit down?. 

Kenan walk was no doubt one of the most amazing experiences there. Even though we did not get to see the sunrise, even though there was not an exciting game going on, we still got to see the kind of spaciousness that you thought you were overlooking yet you were actually being held by, the kind of transition up in the sky from dark to indigo to Carolina blue, the kind of hope that a brand new day granted. 

The following eleven hours went by much more slowly than those hours passed. Still, in no way could I see anyone give up or sit down. ?A new day! Tell yourself you have slept for 8 hours last night?. 

The final two hours answered all the doubts I had in the very beginning, and was definitely the climax of the 24 hours. 

The kid co-captains and their families represented by each dancing team came to the stage. Then there was a fantastic talent show by several kids. The dance performed by the family in pink dresses impressed me a lot. With the most radiant and sincere smile on the face, the little girl on the wheelchair wiggled her arms, forming a heart-warming dance. Waves of cheering broke over the dance--the excitement of atmosphere was no less than that of the scene where everyone sang ?hark the sound? together upon winning the basketball game 20 hours ago. (And yeah, we watched the basketball game together at 8ish on Friday night!) What hundreds of people offered to the kids with physical or mental defect were more support, help, encouragement and love than discrimination or indifference. In such powerful and affecting positive energy, I tried my best to fight back my tears yet still burst into tears. A variety of feelings trigger those tears: tiredness, the power created by all the tough and nice people around you, the warmth brought by the smiles and strength of the kids, the sudden realization of why everyone would stand for 24 hours. Can?t tell for sure which feeling was the most predominant; all of the different feelings mixed and brewed, together moved one to tears. Next, a mom of twins and a dad of a girl shared their stories of their children. The simple and unadorned words and the peaceful tone conveyed the heart wracking yet remarkable stories, making us truly understand the meaning of the 24 hours and the meaning of Dance Marathon. 

The father said, ?It?s like a fortune 5 hundred company, but it?s being run by people that, on top of all of the rigorous studies, on top of, you know basketball games and club sports and Greek life and all the things that take your time to have spent in doing something, you know, it is not just the 24 hours of dance, this goes on the entire year, you will start to have committee meeting in two weeks to start talking about next year. It?s just an unbelievable thing you guys do. I tell Ashlyn all the time 'Become the change you wanna see in the world', and you guys are doing it, thank you guys." I was at the very front of the stage so I could see that the father lowered his head and tried to fight back his tears at times. I guess, there was definitely a touching feeling evoked by hundreds of dancers under the stage and an organization that was making the world better and better bit by bit. 

The chancellor said, ?This is Carolina. This is what I know and love about Carolina. You do great things with style, with energy and are having so much fun.? 

By the end, everyone formed a huge circle, hugging each other shoulder to shoulder even though they didn?t know each other. 

After the 24 hours, the whole gym was filled with balloons of a riot of color; everyone SIT DOWN. 

All doubts have been solved. If before this I were told by someone that you could stand for 24 hours with the help of willpower, I would not believe it. Now I get to understand and believe as well. One does not necessarily need to have a so-called strong body to afford staying up for 24 hours since it is an atmosphere permeated with conviction and love as well as a beautiful goal the 24 hours can help reach that grant one the super power to make it.

What standing for 5 hours and standing for 24 hours can offer to others might be the same but how one feels about standing for 5 hours and 24 hours should absolutely be different. At least my feelings changed every several hours, which was sort of beyond words but was amazing. And I guess feelings are some powerful chemicals that motivate actions so maybe this somehow forms a virtuous cycle. 

But I still don?t have a definite answer as for what I can get from DM, not because it gives me nothing, but because it gives me something too big to express in an accurate way with my clumsy words. It?s genuinely something that one has to experience and feel to gradually understand. 

And some words read from an article occurred to me, ?it isn?t necessary to request answers from life in a hurry; sometimes, you really need to wait with patience. Even if you shouted in a valley, you would need to wait for a while until the long echo finds its way back.?

Before stop writing, I need to thank Renee for giving me the chance to join Pub and leading me to integrate with it, and thank Erin for teaching me all the stuff about video editing and for all the helping and caring, and thank all the girls in Pub for making it a great committee! #Publove

PS: I know this is long-winded, and words just can't do justice to how awesome it was. But trust me, it is too awesome to not to do it.  DO IT TOGETHER NEXT YEAR!!

ID:100002813248009_454019568035147
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

ID:100004253942400_333902410094888
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:A very honorable and respectful bio teacher from high school past away last night from leukemia. I just find this so hard to believe and I can't even breathe right now.
  I am not a top student in bio, but his personal charms deeply influenced me. He knows everything in bio and always always put his students in the first place. He sacrificed a lot for his career as a teacher.
  During these past two years while he was sick, I only checked his social network and asked around from time to time to make sure he is fine, but I never wrote him a letter since I was not his best student thus I am not confident enough. God knows how much I regret not having told him how good a teacher and a man he was, and how he was loved by so many students.
  Say what you want to say when you still have time. 
  At this moment, the scenes of him walking into the classroom and set up the board, writing on the blackboard, staying extra hours to answer questions and help students still keep popping out of my head. Tearing up is far not enough to express my grief and my loss. I refuse to say the word RIP, because my teacher lives in my heart for forever.

ID:100004256923748_311562262329002
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Thanks to everyone who had the courage to come out and have this discussion last night.  It kicked off a shroud of thoughts about my own identity and placement in our society as an Asian-American.  In the future, I hope we can continue these types of events in a more grandiose scale because I believe discussions like these need to happen with a more focused effort on cultural identity in America and awareness of breaking stereotypes.

I'm nowhere remotely close to understanding the complexities of modern society, but I'd like to address Ben Hu's point about whose responsibility it is for Asian-American cultural progression. I think we should look after the representation of the greats in prior civil rights movements (e.g. MLK Jr.) showing that we ourselves, as representatives of this ethnic group, should take matters into our own hands.

Although I am speaking on behalf of Asian-American individuals in this post, I am not narrowing my scope only to this ethnic group.  Yes, the spotlight on Asian-Americans matter to ASA and other Asian-interest organizations, but awareness can only be an inclusive term.  It is such a complicated topic engrained in economics and politics, and anyone who cares about social progress, regardless of their ethnicity, should actively seek to participate in similar discussions moving forward.

Shouts to Unc Akdphi, Unc Kappas, and Unc Lambdas for constituting almost all of the participants in last night's discussion.

ID:100004256923748_305856996232862
Name:Timeline Photos
Story:N/A
Message:I just want to say Happy Founder's Day to UNC LPhiE. A year ago today, I experienced one of the greatest changes in my life by establishing Lambda Phi Epsilon at UNC. Throughout this process of establishing this organization, I've learned the importance of personal development, and I've gained so many valuable experiences and lessons. But the most important thing I've gained is a solid family of brothers who will have my back no matter what and who will never allow me to settle for my second best. To my PM and PD, thank you for the lessons you've taught us and the hard work you've put into shaping this organization. To my brothers, thank you for never allowing me to settle for my second best and shaping me into the person I am today.

"It's not a clique. It's not a crew. It's not your boys back home. It's not a social crutch, a result of some complex or an answer to your insecurities. It's not a best friend, because you don't even have to be friends. It's not someone to eat lunch with, because they don't even have to be there all the time. It's 'I got your back, no matter what.' It's family. It's respect. It's love. It's Eternal Brotherhood."

Story:Varro Wei added 4 photos.
Message:Today, following my auntie and cousins, I finally donated my hair! Because I danced ballet for 10+ years and had to keep my hair at around the same length, I never had a chance to cut it short. I thought I'd cry after haircut but I didn't. But considering someone may feel a little bit better after getting a wig, I'm glad that I've made a right decision. This donation experience taught me how a small act of kindness can make a difference :).

Story:Katrina Wertz posted an event to Facss China's timeline.
Message:This month of February, Carolina China Network is excited to present a discussion entitled China & Africa: Define the Relationship on Friday, February 28th from 4-5pm in Union Room 3206.  We are keen on exposing students on our campus to the myriad of reasons why China has turned attention to Africa?s continent and what opportunities and consequences have come about.  The short one-hour event will be a great chance to come together and eat free Chinese dumplings and discuss economic, diplomatic, and cultural collaborations from a high-level viewpoint.  Our goal is for each person in the room to hear, share, and learn something new about the Sino-Africa relationship that they may not have heard or considered before, and to meet someone in the room that you could continue the conversation with beyond this event!

    ???????????????? ???????????????? ??????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????

 

 

    Jim Morgan  was named  President  and CEO  of Krispy  Kreme Doughnuts, Inc. in January 2008. Mr. Morgan has been a member of the Krispy  Kreme  Board  of Directors  since  2000  and was elected its Chairman in 2005.

 

    Mr. Morgan served as Chairman and CEO of Wachovia Securities following the acquisition of Interstate/Johnson Lane, Inc. (IJL) by Wachovia  Corporation.   He  also  served  as Chairman  and  CEO of Interstate/Johnson Lane, Inc.. Mr. Morgan is a past member of the Securities Industry Association Board of Directors and the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) regional firms committee, and is currently on the Board of Directors of Coca-Coca Bottling Company Consolidated. Mr. Morgan has more than 40 years of business experience and is a

1969 graduate of Vanderbilt University. He also served as a lieutenant in the U.S. Navy.
